      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are experiencing a case of \"leafy gremlins.\" The lower leaves turning yellow could be due to a few reasons, such as overwatering, poor drainage, or a nutrient deficiency, particularly a lack of nitrogen. To fix your soil, you might want to consider a few steps: first, ensure you're not overwatering; second, improve drainage if necessary; and third, you could add some compost or a balanced fertilizer to replenish nutrients. Just remember, when you're dealing with soil, it's always best to be a bit cautious and not overdo it. Too much of a good thing can lead to more problems, like root rot from overwatering or nutrient burn from too much fertilizer. Keep an eye on your plants, and they'll thank you for your careful attention. And remember, in the world of gardening, patience and observation are your best allies. Happy gardening, and may your tomatoes thrive!",
      "source": "target",
